FAC039AA1DEC49CA809452E0F1870107.description:
Demonstrate emergent awareness for conservation,
recycling, and respect for the environment (e.g., turning
off water faucets, using paper from a classroom scrap box
when whole sheets are not needed, keeping the
playground neat and clean).

FA01716681C14B1686EF69699DD66307.description:
Biogeochemical Cycles : The biogeochemical cycles in the Earth systems include the flow of
microscopic and macroscopic resources from one reservoir in the hydrosphere, geosphere,
atmosphere, or biosphere to another, are driven by Earth's internal and external sources of energy,
and are impacted by human activity.

7677B7F470E44D6D93F5097DE7CFFD4D.description:
Climate and Weather : Earth’s weather and climate systems are the result of complex
interactions between land, ocean, ice, and atmosphere.

87DEA52D62C249F6B957EC0C88784D59.description:
Explore the effects of sunlight on living and nonliving
things.

1647A3657AF54B7AA37790F5D4177705.description: Energy in Earth Systems : Internal and external sources of energy drive Earth systems.

DECD3EB810814D48B163C68867BC1BFD.description:
Explore and describe characteristics of and concepts about
soil, rocks, water, and air.

FD7C75AE06B24A23B7AAAB33BB7357FF.description:
Properties of Earth Materials : Earth’s composition is unique, is related to the origin of our
solar system, and provides us with the raw resources needed to sustain life.

5BF1C54A46B54F449C4164A67E29EAE9.description:
Earth Systems Science: All students will understand that Earth operates as a set of complex,
dynamic, and interconnected systems, and is a part of the all-encompassing system of the universe.

AA130ADC072D4D6CB7723F3FB5300E85.description:
Observe and record change over time and cycles of
change that affect living things (e.g., use baby
photographs to discuss human change and growth,
observe and photograph tree growth and leaf changes
throughout the year, monitor the life cycle of a plant).

75095C098DBD4156AA14A1712750E4F0.description:
Heredity and Reproduction : Organisms reproduce, develop, and have predictable life cycles.
Organisms contain genetic information that influences their traits, and they pass this on to their
offspring during reproduction.

167B54B71E5B4BF5BD8469E8EBF4A2D6.description:
Observe and describe how natural habitats provide for the
basic needs of plants and animals with respect to shelter,
food, water, air, and light (e.g., dig outside in the soil to
investigate the kinds of animal life that live in and around
the ground).

053AA31D96B4496B8092E5191E6200DC.description:
Interdependence : All animals and most plants depend on both other organisms and their
environment to meet their basic needs.

D95E6AE01A074890ABBF8D8AA49C6F3E.description:
Observe and describe how plants and animals obtain food
from their environment, such as by observing the
interactions between organisms in a natural habitat.

E2D6B7B7985743FB8FE6D4DF1032266A.description:
Matter and Energy Transformations : Food is required for energy and building cellular
materials. Organisms in an ecosystem have different ways of obtaining food, and some organisms
obtain their food directly from other organisms

EF5853338A3C4BF585A6B8C1F3587ED0.description:
Investigate and compare the basic physical characteristics
of plants, humans, and other animals.

6ED20795D2684C109694C88AE7A66756.description:
Investigate and compare the basic physical characteristics
of plants, humans, and other animals.

C8287C7BF3984027AC82394DD3AE53CF.description:
A. Organization and Development : Living organisms are composed of cellular units (structures)
that carry out functions required for life. Cellular units are composed of molecules, which also carry
out biological functions.

52A5954054F748AAB50E74F1C263DCA6.description:
Life Science: All students will understand that life science principles are powerful conceptual
tools for making sense of the complexity, diversity, and interconnectedness of life on Earth. Order in
natural systems arises in accordance with rules that govern the physical world, and the order of
natural systems can be modeled and predicted through the use of mathematics.

10FBD7A62C2F42B2ACA6A2D42837BCDA.description:
Investigate how and why things move (e.g., slide blocks,
balance structures, push structures over, use ramps to
explore how far and how fast different objects move or
roll).

88CBDE6270284F548008C52390ADE553.description:
Forces and Motion : It takes energy to change the motion of objects. The energy change is
understood in terms of forces.

692CD565B66F4A26B34AD0026F920C20.description:
Predict and confirm the brightness of a light, the volume
of sound, or the amount of heat when given the number
of batteries, or the size of batteries.

5329225255A945D1AC5B3EE091843688.description:
Energy Transfer and Conservation : The conservation of energy can be demonstrated by
keeping track of familiar forms of energy as they are transferred from one object to another.

4FDCAF8375FF48AD83134A1996269749.description:
Investigate sound, heat, and light energy (e.g., the pitch
and volume of sound made by commercially made and
homemade instruments, looking for shadows on the
playground over time and under different weather
conditions) through one or more of the senses.

B8B3AA961D9D4F58862605EA576B7E04.description:
Forms of Energy : Knowing the characteristics of familiar forms of energy, including potential
and kinetic energy, is useful in coming to the understanding that, for the most part, the natural
world can be explained and is predictable.

B6F83F166BB349D3AF53FC297DF3572C.description:
Explore changes in liquids and solids when substances are
combined, heated, or cooled (e.g., mix sand or clay with
various amounts of water; mix different colors of tempera
paints; freeze and melt water and other liquids).

F2FD63B71AD04907AA8972B55EA62D25.description:
Changes in Matter : Substances can undergo physical or chemical changes to form new
substances. Each change involves energy.

D4C00CE3CFD048D8AD81C6DFBFF5AA86.description:
Observe, manipulate, sort, and describe objects and
materials (e.g., water, sand, clay, paint, glue, various
types of blocks, collections of objects, simple household
items that can be taken apart, or objects made of wood,
metal, or cloth) in the classroom and outdoor environment
based on size, shape, color, texture, and weight.

24F1AC3C3E574C46B530397434E1D999.description:
Properties of Matter : All objects and substances in the natural world are composed of matter.
Matter has two fundamental properties: matter takes up space, and matter has inertia.

76BF205A982E4E9C9908CF31CA96042C.description:
Physical Science: All students will understand that physical science principles, including
fundamental ideas about matter, energy, and motion, are powerful conceptual tools for making
sense of phenomena in physical, living, and Earth systems science.

5DF22BE42F4346F2BF8659187DF4F70E.description:
Represent observations and work through drawing,
recording data, and “writing.”

C17D3C5FD1A14787A93575A9996DA9F3.description:
Participate Productively in Science : The growth of scientific knowledge involves critique and
communication, which are social practices that are governed by a core set of values and norms.

56F45C8FF6BC4EC4BA6AD43BE2D01EE3.description:
Communicate with other children and adults to share
observations, pursue questions, and make predictions
and/or conclusions.

5A5D306CEB2B42CB8C683F19B285F94A.description: Reflect on Scientific Knowledge : Scientific knowledge builds on itself over time.

19B7BF0A036647E884EE7672AF4DBEB2.description:
Identify and use basic tools and technology to extend
exploration in conjunction with science investigations.

335F04EBF6EE48159998D8478D2DA2F4.description:
Use basic science terms and topic-related science
vocabulary.

06F56E2576F945419D3B128D1E50AC9B.description:
Observe, question, predict, and investigate materials,
objects, and phenomena (e.g., using simple tools to crack
a nut and look inside) during indoor and outdoor
classroom activities and during any longer-term
investigations.

1437C90011FA424D8A40F3092A719ECD.description:
Generate Scientific Evidence Through Active Investigations : Students master the
conceptual, mathematical, physical, and computational tools that need to be applied when
constructing and evaluating claims.

E1E415CB3D774A27A1B9CBEECCC10428.description:
Display curiosity about science objects, materials,
activities, and longer-term investigations in progress.

068AFCBFFC0C436DB861BB124B67654C.description:
Understand Scientific Explanations : Students understand core concepts and principles of
science and use measurement and observation tools to assist in categorizing, representing, and
interpreting the natural and designed world.

E62D35A11FAA4FF49B504BC08A9F7065.description:
Science Practices: All students will understand that science is both a body of knowledge and
an evidence-based, model-building enterprise that continually extends, refines, and revises
knowledge. The four Science Practices strands encompass the knowledge and reasoning skills that
students must acquire to be proficient in science.
